Focus definitely takes practice. What has worked for me, both for writing and reading, has been:
Turn off computer, phone, everything. Everything electronic, but especially things with internet connections.
If you have a back yard and the weather is okay, sit there, with pen and paper.
Otherwise, just sit with whatever you'll use to write, and if you aren't writing, let yourself daydream, but don't actually do anything else that's like, a fun activity.
Writing, or daydreaming, or maybe cooking.

>Otherwise, just sit with whatever you'll use to write, and if you aren't writing, let yourself daydream, but don't actually do anything else that's like, a fun activity.
Neil Gaiman describes something like that: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iHPKTby9z6o

The point he makes is that writing should be the most fun thing available to you. It's okay if you're not writing and you don't have to beat yourself up about that. You just need to create a situation where you'll spend the next two hours staring out the window or walking aimlessly around your neighbourhood if you don't write.

It's pretty rare to say "I was trapped on the plane for 18 hours and I just couldn't get any reading done" because planes are so fucking boring that reading becomes easy.
